🤖 TelegramBot Reward System
A production-ready Telegram bot built with Node.js, Express, and Firebase — featuring user registration, referral tracking, task completion, payout management, and a full admin dashboard.

✨ Features
Webhook-based architecture — low latency, scalable, no polling overhead
Referral system — users register via referral links; referrers are tracked automatically
Task engine — admins create tasks; users complete them to earn rewards
Payout management — configurable pool and minimum payout thresholds
Admin dashboard — inline keyboard UI with ban, search, pool control, and payout tools
Ban & maintenance system — instantly toggle bot access or block individual users
Firebase Firestore — persistent user state, task records, and registration flow
Health check endpoint — /health for uptime monitoring and deployment checks

🏗️ Project Structure
├── index.js                  # Entry point — Express server, webhook, routing
├── handlers/
│   ├── userHandler.js        # Dashboard, earn screen, user callbacks
│   ├── adminHandler.js       # Admin dashboard, ban, search, pool, payout
│   ├── taskHandler.js        # Task creation, completion, admin task UI
│   └── registrationHandler.js# Multi-step registration, group verification
├── firebase.js               # Firestore initialization
├── .env                      # Environment config (not committed)
└── package.json

⚙️ Environment Variables
Create a .env file in the project root:
BOT_TOKEN=your_telegram_bot_token
WEBHOOK_URL=https://your-domain.com
ADMIN_IDS=123456789,987654321
PORT=3000
Variable
Description
BOT_TOKEN
Telegram bot token from @BotFather
WEBHOOK_URL
Public HTTPS URL where Telegram sends updates
ADMIN_IDS
Comma-separated Telegram user IDs with admin access
PORT
Port for the Express server (default: 3000)


🚀 Getting Started
1. Install dependencies
npm install
2. Configure Firebase
Place your Firebase service account credentials in firebase.js or set them via environment variables. Ensure Firestore is enabled in your Firebase project.
3. Set up your .env file
See the Environment Variables section above.
4. Run the server
node index.js
The server will start and automatically register the webhook with Telegram:
Server running on port 3000
Webhook set to: https://your-domain.com/bot<token>
📡 Endpoints
Method
Path
Description
POST
/bot<token>
Telegram webhook receiver
GET
/health
Returns { status: 'OK', botActive }

👤 User Flow
/start
  ├── Admin → Admin Dashboard
  └── User
        ├── Already registered → Dashboard
        └── New user → Registration flow
              └── Optional referral code tracking
Registration
Users go through a multi-step registration handled by RegistrationHandler. Group membership verification is required before completing registration.

🛡️ Admin Commands
Command
Description
/start
Opens the admin dashboard
/ban <userId>
Bans a user from the bot
/stop
Puts the bot into maintenance mode
/on
Reactivates the bot for all users
/set_pool <amount>
Sets the reward pool value
/set_min <amount>
Sets the minimum payout threshold
/search <query>
Searches users by username or ID
/task
Opens the task management dashboard

📋 Task System
Admins create tasks via the /task command through an inline keyboard flow. Users see available tasks in their dashboard, complete them, and submit for verification. Task state during creation is held in memory via taskHandler.taskCreationState.

💰 Payout Flow
Admin sets pool via /set_pool
Admin sets minimum payout via /set_min
Admin initiates payout (start_payout callback)
Admin confirms (confirm_payout callback)
AdminHandler distributes rewards to eligible users

🔒 Security
All admin commands are gated by ADMIN_IDS — only listed user IDs can trigger admin actions
Banned users receive an immediate rejection message and cannot interact with the bot
Maintenance mode blocks all non-admin users with a friendly notice
Webhook path includes the bot token, making it unguessable by default

🧰 Tech Stack
Layer
Technology
